Line plots - geom_line()

The typical use for geom_line() is time series data, where we have records of a given observational unit over time. For example, the dataset aus_arrivals, loaded along fpp3, contains records of the number of arrivals to Australia from different countries of origin: Japan, NZ, UK and US.

In these case we have four observational units that we measure over time:

  1. Arrivals from Japan to Australia
  2. Arrivals from New Zealand to Australia
  3. Arrivals from UK to Australia
  4. Arrivals from US to Australia

Lets confirm the unique values of the variable Origin

aus_arrivals

# Unique values of variable Origin (country of origin)
aus_arrivals %>% pull(Origin) %>% unique()
[1] "Japan" "NZ"    "UK"    "US"

First let us use geom_line() to create a plot of the arrivals to australia from Japan. For convenience, we are going to store the resulting ggplot graph in a new object called p1 (plot 1)

p1 <- 
  aus_arrivals %>% 
    filter(Origin == "Japan") %>% # Limit observations to those from Japan
    ggplot(aes(x = Quarter, y = Arrivals)) +
    geom_line()

# Show p1
p1

geom_line() + geom_point()

Importantly, note that the lines are joining together discrete observations! That is, we do not have a continuous measure of the arrivals from Japan to Australia, but rather only observations every quarter. This is most clear when we super-impose the specific observations with geom_point(). Starting from the previous ggpplot object p1, we may add a geom_point() layer to it:

p1 + geom_point()

Most of the time the points depicting the exact observations are committed from a line plot, but other times they may be included, depending on how explicit you want/need to be about them.

groups and color

The groups argument can be used to create a different line for each group. This may be necessary in cases where we have a time series for different observational units in our dataset. For example, in the datset aus_arrivals we have time series for the arrivals to Australia from different countries of origin. In this case each country of origin is a different observational unit.

If we want to depict a different line plot for every observational unit (in this case country of origin), we need to specify these observational units as the groups argument within aes.

aus_arrivals %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Quarter, y = Arrivals,
             group = Origin)) +
  geom_line()

However, that graph is not very clear, because every line is black. To solve this issue, we may directly specify the groups using the argument color (groups is now no longer necessary, it becomes redundant with colors):

aus_arrivals %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Quarter, y = Arrivals,
             color = Origin)) +
  geom_line()

What happens if we do not use the variable Origin to segregate groups or by color?? Then for every quarter (for every point in the x-axis) we would have four observations. geom_line() would join these with a vertical line and then continue to the next quarter (next x-axis point). This graph would not make any sense at all. This is easiest to see if we overlay the observations using geom_point() to understand what is going on. The graph below is wrong but we plot it to illustrate the previous points:

# This graph is WRONG
aus_arrivals %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Quarter, y = Arrivals)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() + 
  ggtitle("This graph is WRONG")

geom_line() + facetting

Of course, facetting is also applicable. In fact, an alternative to using groups to depict the four countries of origin within the same graph would be to use facet_wrap():

aus_arrivals %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Quarter, y = Arrivals, 
             color = Origin)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_wrap("Origin")

We could also have used facet_grid(). In this particular case we only want to facet following a single variable (Origin), so we need to use . to indicate this. Remember the syntax:

aus_arrivals %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Quarter, y = Arrivals, 
             color = Origin)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_grid(Origin ~ .) # facet the variable Origin row-wise

aus_arrivals %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Quarter, y = Arrivals, 
             color = Origin)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_grid(. ~ Origin) # facet the variable Origin column-wise

geom_line() + geom_smooth()

You may add a smoothing line to geom_line() to identify the evolution of the trend regardless of the short-term fluctuations. Use a non-linear method such as "gam" (or loess if you have less than 1000 points) and specify se = FALSE to remove the confidence intervals (se stands for standard error):

  aus_arrivals %>% 
    ggplot(aes(x = Quarter, y = Arrivals, 
               color = Origin)) +
    geom_line() + 
    geom_smooth(method = "gam", se = FALSE)
`geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

Note that, because we specified the argument color within the highest level aes() (the one within the function ggplot()), the colouring also applies to geom_smooth().

For noisy data, smoothing is sensible as well. For example, the dataset vic_elec contains half-hourly electricity consumption (average value) for the region of Victoria in Australia. Because of the high number of measurements, and the fluctuations in energy consumption within the day, weeks and months (different time periods), the data is very noisy. We may extract a trend using geom_smooth()

The dataset global_economy, loaded along with the library fpp3 contains multiple time series of different economic measures for a number of countries. Let us first filter the data corresponding to Spainâs imports and exports

sp_exports_imports <- 
  global_economy %>%
  filter(Country == "Spain") %>% 
  select(Year, Imports, Exports)

sp_exports_imports
# A tsibble: 58 x 3 [1Y]

Currently the dataset is such that it has:

  1. One row per year
  2. Imports registered in one column and Exports registered in another column

To be able to handle this data more easily in ggplot2, it is sensible to reformat it. Specifically we want to:

  1. Create a new categorical variable called measure that will take the values either Imports or Exports
  2. Expand the number of rows of the dataset to have two rows per year. One row will correspond to Imports and one row to Exports
  3. A third column called values will hold the corresponding value of Imports and Exports within each year.

That is, we want our dataset to look as follows:

# A tsibble: 116 x 3 [1Y]
# Key:       measure [2]
    Year measure value
   <dbl> <chr>   <dbl>
 1  1960 Imports  6.90
 2  1960 Exports  8.37
 3  1961 Imports  8.60
 4  1961 Exports  7.97
 5  1962 Imports 10.1 
 6  1962 Exports  8.30
 7  1963 Imports 10.8 
 8  1963 Exports  7.71
 9  1964 Imports 11.4 
10  1964 Exports  8.81
# â¦ with 106 more rows

We can achieve this using pivot_longer() from the library dplyr as follows:

sp_exports_imports <- 
  sp_exports_imports %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = Imports:Exports, # Columns we want to re-shape (cols from Imports to Exports)
               names_to = "measure", # Name of the new categorical variable
               values_to = "value")

sp_exports_imports
# A tsibble: 116 x 3 [1Y]
# Key:       measure [2]
    Year measure value
   <dbl> <chr>   <dbl>
 1  1960 Imports  6.90
 2  1960 Exports  8.37
 3  1961 Imports  8.60
 4  1961 Exports  7.97
 5  1962 Imports 10.1 
 6  1962 Exports  8.30
 7  1963 Imports 10.8 
 8  1963 Exports  7.71
 9  1964 Imports 11.4 
10  1964 Exports  8.81
# â¦ with 106 more rows

This format may indeed be less clear for a human reader, but from ggplotâs perspective it is better, because it allows us to specify the values Imports and Exports within the aes() function as the values of a single categorical variable called measure.

NOTE: pivot_longer() and pivot_wider() are important dataframe operations when working with ggplot2 and you should become familiar with them. A short notebook dedicated to explaining these operations will be released.

Now that you have the data in an appropriate format for ggplot() to work with it, create the following graphs:

  • HINT use + ylab("% of GDP") to label the y-axis and + ggtitle("Spain's Exports and Imports") to print the title.
sp_exports_imports %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Year, y = value, color = measure)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  ylab("% of GDP") +
  ggtitle("Spain's Exports and Imports")

sp_exports_imports %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Year, y = value, color = measure)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  facet_grid(measure ~ .) +
  ylab("% of GDP") +
  ggtitle("Spain's Exports and Imports")

The code below:

  1. Creates a column date indicating the date of each flight using make_date() from the library lubridate.
  2. Computes the av_delay, max_delay and min_delay of the flights upon arrival to their destination for each of the three airports of origin in NY (variable origin) for a given date.
  3. Re-orders the columns, placing date, wday and month at the front and then every other column present
# Load lubridate if it is not loaded
# Load nycflights if it is not loaded
library(nycflights13)
library(lubridate) # In case it is not loaded.
                   # This should not be placed here, but I put it to prevent
                   # errors in your code. PLace it at the beginning of the document
library(tidyverse) # In case it is not loaded.
                   # This should not be placed here, but I put it to prevent
                   # errors in your code. PLace it at the beginning of the document

delays <- 
  
  flights %>% 
  
    # 1. Create a new date column
    mutate(
      date = make_date(year, month, day)
    ) %>% 
  
    # 2. group_by and summarise
    #    the variables month and day are included so that
    #    they are present in the summary dataframe, but they do not affect
    #    the computation.
    group_by(month, day, origin, date) %>% 
    summarise(
      av_delay = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
      max_delay = max(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
      min_delay = min(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE)
    ) %>% 
  
    # So that subsequent operations are not performed group-wise
    ungroup() %>% 
  
    # 3. Reorder columns
    select(date, month, everything())
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'month', 'day', 'origin'. You can override
using the `.groups` argument.

Boxplots - geom_boxplot()

A box-plot is a plot summarizing a distribution. It represents in a succint manner the following magnitudes of a given distribution/sample (the figure below follows Tukeyâs classic definition, the defauly in ggplot):

The figure above includes the actual observations summarized by the box-plot (red points). These are normally ommited, since the box-plot is a summary. The final aspect would therefore be:

Boxplots in ggplot2

We can use geom_boxplot() to produce boxplots in ggplot2. For example, we might produce box-plots to summarize the distributions of the depth of diamonds for the different cuts:

ggplot(diamonds, aes(y=depth, x=cut, fill= cut)) + 
  geom_boxplot()

These boxplots tell us that the diamonds of cut Fair have many more outliers in terms of depth than the rest of the categories. They also have a noticeable greater median depth. Diamonds with cut ideal also have a substantial ammount of points that could be considered outliers or extremes of its distribution. Diamonds with cuts Good, Very good, Premium and Ideal have a fairly similar median depth.

We may even further split the study using the clarity within each color by specifying a fill following yet another categorical variable (in this case, clarity)

ggplot(diamonds, aes(y=depth, x=cut, fill=clarity)) +
  geom_boxplot()

Time-series of box-plots

Box-plots can come in handy for the analysis of time-series data.

For example, the PBS dataset contained in the fpp3 package details the costs of Medicare prescriptions Australia. Let us first filter for a specific kind of drugs (antidiabetic drugs, corresponding to ATC2 == "A10") and then add all the costs per month (using group_by).

a10 <-
  
PBS %>% as_tibble() %>% 
  
  filter(ATC2 == "A10") %>%
  
  group_by(Month) %>% 
  
  summarise(TotalC = sum(Cost) / 1e6)

Exercise BP. 2 - factor()

Now using the function year() on the column Month of the a10 dataframe, create a new variable (column) signalling the year for each observation and call it year. Then produce the graph below, which is a time series of box-plots summarising the distribution of observations within each year.

  • Hint: you need to use factor(year) and not year as the x aesthetic for this to work. This signals to ggplot that it should treat the variable year as a categorical despite it being of type double.
  • NOTE: the function year() is part of the lubridate package, which was loaded along with fpp3.
a10 <-
  a10 %>% 
  mutate(year = year(Month))

a10 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = factor(year), y = TotalC)) +
  geom_boxplot()

This graph shows several things:

1. As we could see in the line plot (or time-plot), the level of the cost of 
antiadiabatic medication has been raising over the years.

2. Not only this, within each year the variability of the total cost 
each month has increased as well. This is recognisable in the increasingly 
bigger IQR of the graphs.

Heatmaps - geom_tile()

To generate a heatmap you need:

  • Two categorical variables one for the x-axis and one for the y-axis
  • One continuous variable to be used as the fill argument of aes

Heatmap example 1 - total value of diamonds in the dataset in each subgroup of color and cut

The first thing we need to do is to use group_by() to compute the sum of the prices of all the diamonds within each group defined by cut and color.

diamonds_val <- 
  diamonds %>% 
    group_by(cut, color) %>% 
    summarize(
      value = sum(price, na.rm=TRUE)
    ) %>% 
    ungroup()
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'cut'. You can override using the `.groups`
argument.
diamonds_val
# A tibble: 35 Ã 3
   cut   color   value
   <ord> <ord>   <int>
 1 Fair  D      699443
 2 Fair  E      824838
 3 Fair  F     1194025
 4 Fair  G     1331126
 5 Fair  H     1556112
 6 Fair  I      819953
 7 Fair  J      592103
 8 Good  D     2254363
 9 Good  E     3194260

Once we have this, let us see how we could generate a heat map and examine its output:

ggplot(diamonds_val, aes(x=cut, y=color, fill=value)) +
  
  # Create tiles and adjust their areas to ensure adequate spacing between them
  geom_tile(aes(width=0.96, height = 0.95)) +
  
  # Print the values within each tile
  geom_text(aes(label=value)) + 
  
  # Define a custom color scale.
  scale_fill_gradient(low="#eff3ff", high="#084594") + 
  
  # Use white background to enhance spacing effect between tiles
  theme(panel.background=element_rect(fill='white'))

Analysis of the output

For each combination of cut an color, we get the total number of diamonds in that group. The colors of the tiles help identify values. Clearly the combination Ideal and G contains the biggest amount of observations.

Heatmap example 2 - correlation matrix - diamonds dataset

A correlation matrix can be made very clear using a heatmap visualization.

First, we select all the numerical variables (the ones for which it makes sense to compute the correlation coefficient). We do this by using where(is.numeric) in combination with select. Let us understand how this works:

  • is.numeric returns TRUE if a given variable or vector is of type numeric. For example, the code below evaluates to TRUE because the variable carat is of type numeric:
diamonds %>% pull(carat) %>% is.numeric()
[1] TRUE
  • where() is a function that can be used to select variables of a dataframe for which a function returns TRUE. For example, the code below selects all the numerical variables (columns for which is.numeric() evaluates to true):
# Select variables for which the function
diamonds %>% select(where(is.numeric))

We make use of this to select only the numeric variables prior to computing the correlation matrix:

corr_matrix <- 
  
  diamonds %>% 
  
    # Selects only variables of type "numeric" for which pearsons corr. coeff makes sense
    select(where(is.numeric)) %>%
    
    # Computes correlation matrix between the numerical variables
    cor()

The result is an R matrix. We have not seen this data structure, but you may think of it as a two-dimensional vector. In any case, we are going to turn it into a dataframe using:

  1. The function reshape2::melt() (function melt() from the reshape2 package). Turns the wide-format corr_matrix to long format. This will leave the data in a format much more adequate for ggplot2.

  2. Then we will round the correlation coefficients to 2 decimals to be able to include them in our graph

Let us proceed with reshape2::melt

aux_corr <- 
  
  corr_matrix %>% 
  
  reshape2::melt()

The function reshape2::melt() is essentially equivalent to pivot_longer(), but applicable to an R matrix rather than a dataframe. Lets explain its output.

As you can see instead of having a single column for each variable detailing the correlation coefficient with the rest of the variables, the corresponding wide-format returned by reshape2::melt() has two categorical columns Var1 and Var2 detailing the combination of variables and a third column value detailing the value of the correlation coefficient corresponding to that combination.

In the next step we round the column value to two decimals. This is necessary to print the actual value on the heatmap (you will understand this when you see the result):

aux_corr <- 
  aux_corr %>% 
    mutate(
      value = round(value, 2)
    )

This data is now fit to produce a heatmap of the correlation matrix in ggplot2 thanks to having the categoricals X1 and X2. Note that we detail rev(X2) to invert the order of the labels of the variables along the y-axis. I encourage you to remove rev() and re-run the code to examine the result:

aux_corr %>% 
  
  ggplot(aes(x = Var1, y = Var2, fill = value)) + # Rev reverses the order of the
                                                   # categorical y axis
  
  # Create the tiles and adjust the area to ensure adequate spacing
  geom_tile(aes(width = 0.965, height = 0.95)) +
  
  # Reverse the y-axis so that the 1s of the matrix are on the main
  # diagonal of the matrix
  scale_y_discrete(limits=rev) +
  
  # Print the corr values within the tiles
  geom_text(aes(label=value)) +
  
  # Define a gradient color scale with two ends
  # Further on this command on  the notebook on graph customization
  scale_fill_gradient2() +
  
  # Use white background as spacing within the tiles
  theme(panel.background=element_rect(fill='white')) + 
  
  ylab("") + xlab("") + # Remove the x-axis and y-axis labels
  
  ggtitle("correlation matrix - diamonds dataset") # print the title

Note that we used scale_fill_gradient2() because the correlation coefficient has two relevant extreme values (-1 and 1), so our color scale requires two such extremes. This is explained in detail in the notebook on graphs customisation, where we will repeat this example and learn how to further taylor the color scale.

Heatmap example 3 - Calendar heatmap

The vic_elec dataset, from the fpp3 package, contains half-hourly electricity consumption records for the region of Victoria in Australia.

The code below computes the average daily demand and then creates variables detailing the year, month and the day of the month corresponding to each date. Finally it filters observations corresponding to 2012 and stores the result in a variable called aux (auxiliary)

  • NOTE: the functions year(), month() and mday() are part of the lubridate package, which was loaded along with fpp3.
aux <-
  
vic_elec %>%
  
  as_tibble() %>% # Ensure the object is a tibble
  
  group_by(Date) %>% # GroupBy day
  
  # Compute average daily demand
  summarize(
    avg_demand_MWh = mean(Demand, na.rm=TRUE)
  ) %>%
  
  # Extract year, month and day of the month
  mutate(
    year = year(Date),
    month = month(Date, label = TRUE, abbr = FALSE),
    mday = mday(Date)
  ) %>% 
  
  # Filter for observations in 2012
  filter(year == 2012)

aux

Finally the code below computes the calendar heatmap:

aux %>% 
  
  ggplot(aes(x = factor(mday), y = month, fill = avg_demand_MWh)) + 
  
  # Create the tiles and adjust heir areas to ensure adequate spacing
  geom_tile(aes(width=.93, height=.955)) +
  
  theme(
        # Set background to white to show between tiles
        panel.background=element_rect(fill='white'),
        
        # Rotate the labels of the x-axis
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1)
        ) +
  
  # Define custom gradient scale
  scale_fill_gradient(low="#eff3ff", high="#084594") +
  
  # Set label for x-axis
  xlab("Days") +
  
  # Set label for y-axis
  ylab("Months") +  

  # Set title
  ggtitle("Average daily electricity consumption in the region of Victoria")

Exercise HM. 1 - Heatmap calendar of weekly data

The dataset us_gasoline contains the finished motor gasoline product supplied in the US in million barrels per day.

The code below computes variables corresponding to the year - month and week of each observation and finally filters for years between 2010 and 2016 (included)

  • NOTE: the functions year(), month() and epiweek() are part of the lubridate package, which was loaded along with fpp3.
aux_gasoline <- 
  
  # Dataset loaded along the fpp3 library
  us_gasoline %>% 
  
    # Ensure the data is a tibble and not a dataframe
    as_tibble() %>% 
  
    # Create new variables for the year, month and week of the year
    mutate(
      year = year(Week),
      month = month(Week, label = TRUE, abbr = FALSE),
      week = epiweek(Week)
    ) %>% 
  
  # Fitlter for years between 2010 and 2016 (included)
  filter(year >= 2010) %>% 
  filter(year < 2017)

Exercise HM. 2 - Pedestrians dataset

The dataset pedestrian, loaded along with the fpp3 library, contains hourly pedestrian counts from 2015-01-01 to 2016-12-31 at 4 sensors in the city of Melbourne.

The code below filters data for a specific sensor and then aggregates the data to compute the total pedestrian counts per day at the location of this sensor. It then creates variables signalling the year, the month and the day of the month associated to each day and filters for observations in the year 2016. The result is stored in aux_ped

  • NOTE: the functions year(), month() and mday() are part of the lubridate package, which was loaded along with fpp3.
aux_ped <- 
  pedestrian %>% 
  
    # Ensure data is a tibble
    as_tibble() %>% 
  
    # Filter data for a specific sensor
    filter(Sensor == "Birrarung Marr") %>% 
    
    # Compute
    group_by(Date) %>% 
    summarise(
      pedestrians = sum(Count)
    ) %>% 
  
    # Create variables for year, month and day of the month
    mutate(
      year = year(Date),
      month = month(Date, label = TRUE, abbr = FALSE),
      mday = mday(Date) 
    ) %>% 
  
    # Filter for observations in 2016
    filter(year == 2016)

Exercise HM. 3 - New York City Flights

The code below is very similar to the code in exercise LP. 2 computing the dataframe delays, with the difference being that now the averages will be computed per week-day. Refer to that exercise for the details:

# Load lubridate if it is not loaded
# Load nycflights if it is not loaded
library(nycflights13)
library(lubridate) # Loads lubridate in case it is not loaded.
                   # This should not be placed here, but I put it to prevent
                   # errors in your code. Place it at the beginning of the document
library(tidyverse) # Loads tidyverse in case it is not loaded.
                   # This should not be placed here, but I put it to prevent
                   # errors in your code. Place it at the beginning of the document

delays_wday <- 
  
  flights %>% 
  
    # 1. Create a new date column and the corresponding week_day
    mutate(
      date = make_date(year, month, day),
      
      # Compute the weekday from the date.
        # label = TRUE - character format instead of number
        # abbr = TRUE - abbreviated format instead of full format
      wday = wday(date, label = TRUE, abbr = TRUE)
    ) %>% 
  
    # 2. group_by and summarise
    group_by(origin, month, wday) %>% 
    summarise(
      av_delay = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
      max_delay = max(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
      min_delay = min(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE)
    ) %>% 
  
    # So that subsequent operations are not performed group-wise
    ungroup()
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'origin', 'month'. You can override using
the `.groups` argument.
